## Example 4 — Verify Identities Using Sum/Difference Formulas

Verify [cos(60 degrees + theta) = sin(30 degrees - theta)]

### Step 1: Apply Cosine Sum Identity

[cos(60 degrees + theta) = cos 60 degrees cos theta - sin 60 degrees sin theta]

[= (1/2) cos theta - (sqrt(3)/2) sin theta]

### Step 2: Apply Sine Difference Identity

[sin(30 degrees - theta) = sin 30 degrees cos theta - cos 30 degrees sin theta]

[= (1/2) cos theta - (sqrt(3)/2) sin theta]

### Step 3: Conclude

Both expressions match. Verified.

## Example 5 — Use Sum/Difference Identities to Write Single Expressions

Write [sin 19 degrees cos 11 degrees + cos 19 degrees sin 11 degrees] as a single trigonometric function.

### Step 1: Recognize the Pattern

This matches [sin A cos B + cos A sin B = sin(A + B)]

### Step 2: Apply

[sin 19 degrees cos 11 degrees + cos 19 degrees sin 11 degrees = sin(19 degrees + 11 degrees) = sin 30 degrees]

### Step 3: State the Value

[sin 30 degrees = 1/2]

